---
const bizName = "SureSwim Pool & Spa";
---

<!doctype html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
<meta charset="UTF-8" />
<meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1" />
<title>Approach — {bizName}</title>

<style>
:root {
  --text: #0f172a;
  --muted: #475569;
  --border: #e2e8f0;
  --accent: #0b5ed7;
  --bg-soft: #f8fafc;
}

* { box-sizing: border-box; }

body {
  margin: 0;
  font-family: system-ui, -apple-system, BlinkMacSystemFont, "Segoe UI", sans-serif;
  color: var(--text);
  background: #fff;
  line-height: 1.75;
}

header {
  border-bottom: 1px solid var(--border);
}

nav {
  max-width: 1100px;
  margin: auto;
  padding: 14px 20px;
  display: flex;
  justify-content: space-between;
  align-items: center;
}

nav a {
  font-size: 14px;
  color: var(--muted);
  text-decoration: none;
}

main {
  max-width: 1100px;
  margin: auto;
  padding: 64px 20px;
}

h1 {
  font-size: clamp(36px, 5vw, 56px);
  letter-spacing: -0.03em;
  margin-bottom: 20px;
}

h2 {
  margin-top: 64px;
  margin-bottom: 16px;
  font-size: 28px;
  letter-spacing: -0.02em;
}

p {
  max-width: 78ch;
  color: var(--muted);
  margin-bottom: 18px;
}

.menu {
  display: grid;
  grid-template-columns: repeat(auto-fit, minmax(280px, 1fr));
  gap: 24px;
  margin-top: 24px;
}

.card {
  border: 1px solid var(--border);
  border-radius: 16px;
  padding: 22px;
  background: #fff;
}

.card h3 {
  margin-top: 0;
  margin-bottom: 8px;
  font-size: 18px;
}

.card p {
  margin: 0;
  font-size: 15px;
  color: var(--muted);
}

.soft {
  background: var(--bg-soft);
  padding: 48px 32px;
  border-radius: 24px;
}

footer {
  margin-top: 80px;
  border-top: 1px solid var(--border);
  padding-top: 32px;
  font-size: 14px;
  color: var(--muted);
}

footer a {
  color: var(--accent);
  text-decoration: none;
}
</style>
</head>

<body>

<header>
  <nav>
    <strong>{bizName}</strong>
    <a href="/">← Back to home</a>
  </nav>
</header>

<main>

<!-- INTRO -->
<section>
  <h1>Approach</h1>

  <p>
    This page exists for homeowners who want to understand how their pool is actually being
    cared for — beyond surface cleaning and weekly routines.
  </p>

  <p>
    I’ve been involved in pool service most of my life, working alongside my dad as he ran his
    own pool business for nearly two decades. That experience taught me that clean water is
    not accidental — it’s the result of consistent decisions made over time.
  </p>

  <p>
    I started SureSwim to take that foundation and approach it more deliberately.
    Slower where needed. More thoughtful. More accountable.
  </p>
</section>

<!-- CORE PHILOSOPHY -->
<section class="soft">
  <h2>Core philosophy</h2>

  <div class="menu">
    <div class="card">
      <h3>Clean is the outcome</h3>
      <p>
        A clean pool is the visible result. The real work happens in how the system is set up,
        balanced, and maintained between visits.
      </p>
    </div>

    <div class="card">
      <h3>Pools are systems</h3>
      <p>
        Water, circulation, filtration, plumbing, and environment all interact. Treating them
        separately creates drift.
      </p>
    </div>

    <div class="card">
      <h3>Stability beats correction</h3>
      <p>
        Preventing problems is quieter, cheaper, and more effective than fixing them after
        they appear.
      </p>
    </div>

    <div class="card">
      <h3>One accountable mind</h3>
      <p>
        I work on every pool myself. The person observing the issue is the same person solving it.
      </p>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

<!-- SYSTEM THINKING -->
<section>
  <h2>System-level thinking</h2>

  <p>
    Most pool problems don’t come from one obvious failure. They come from small misalignments
    that compound over time.
  </p>

  <div class="menu">
    <div class="card">
      <h3>Equipment awareness</h3>
      <p>
        Filters, seals, unions, bypasses, valves, and check valves are monitored for behavior,
        not just presence.
      </p>
    </div>

    <div class="card">
      <h3>Flow & interaction</h3>
      <p>
        Spas, waterfalls, cleaners, and returns affect each other. I pay attention to how
        features interact with the main pump.
      </p>
    </div>

    <div class="card">
      <h3>Methodical troubleshooting</h3>
      <p>
        Observe → adjust → verify → remember. No guesswork. No overcorrection.
      </p>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

<!-- CHEMISTRY -->
<section class="soft">
  <h2>Chemistry as a system</h2>

  <div class="menu">
    <div class="card">
      <h3>Liquid-first sanitation</h3>
      <p>
        Predictable, controllable chlorine behavior with minimal long-term side effects.
      </p>
    </div>

    <div class="card">
      <h3>Stabilizer awareness</h3>
      <p>
        CYA is managed intentionally to avoid chemical creep and loss of control.
      </p>
    </div>

    <div class="card">
      <h3>Balance, not chasing numbers</h3>
      <p>
        pH, alkalinity, and calcium are treated as a system, not isolated test results.
      </p>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

<!-- OPERATIONAL GOALS -->
<section>
  <h2>Operational goals</h2>

  <div class="menu">
    <div class="card">
      <h3>Between-visit cleanliness</h3>
      <p>
        A pool should stay clean even when I’m not there. Setup matters.
      </p>
    </div>

    <div class="card">
      <h3>Efficiency awareness</h3>
      <p>
        Runtime, electricity use, and wear are balanced against cleanliness and safety.
      </p>
    </div>

    <div class="card">
      <h3>Reduced manual intervention</h3>
      <p>
        The best system requires less hands-on correction over time, not more.
      </p>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

<!-- CLOSING -->
<section>
  <h2>The result</h2>

  <p>
    A pool that looks clean, behaves predictably, and quietly supports itself.
    Care that’s most noticeable when I’m not there — and least noticeable when everything
    is working as it should.
  </p>
</section>

<footer>
  <p>
    <a href="/">← Back to home</a>
  </p>
</footer>

</main>

</body>
</html>
